  "prompt": "What is the legal history of money laundering prohibitions?",
  "response": "Money laundering laws have evolved significantly over time, with key developments including:\n\n1. Early Origins\n- Informal prohibitions existed against hiding proceeds of criminal activity\n- Limited legal frameworks before mid-20th century\n\n2. Bank Secrecy Act (1970) - United States\n- First comprehensive legal framework addressing financial reporting\n- Required financial institutions to report large cash transactions\n- Established reporting requirements to detect potential criminal activity\n\n3. International Developments\n- 1980s: Increased focus on drug trafficking proceeds\n- 1989: Financial Action Task Force (FATF) established\n- Developed international standards for combating money laundering\n\n4. Major Legislative Milestones\n- 1986: Money Laundering Control Act (U.S.)\n- 1990: Specific criminal penalties for money laundering\n- 2001: USA PATRIOT Act expanded anti-money laundering regulations\n\n5. Global Expansion\n- Increasing international cooperation\n- United Nations conventions\n- Regional regulatory frameworks\n- Expanding scope beyond drug trafficking to broader criminal proceeds\n\n6. Contemporary Approach\n- Comprehensive regulatory compliance requirements\n- Advanced technological monitoring\n- Increased focus on cryptocurrency and digital transactions\n\nThis overview represents a general progression of money laundering legal prohibitions internationally.",
